is=20
3-to-1 or less; it is out of balance if the ratio is more than 3 to 1.

Although rates vary by state, the companies said the average rate for=20
in-balance traffic is $0.0032 cents per minute.  The average rate for=20
out-of-balance traffic is $0.0018 per minute (retroactive to Sept. 1, 2001)=
=20
and declines to an average of $0.00101 by June 1, 2002.  The agreement runs=
=20
through May 2003.

=0F"Our agreement should be helpful to state and federal regulators,=0F" sa=
id=20
Tricia Paoletta, vice president-government relations at Level 3.

=0F"This freely negotiated agreement proves that a reasonable solution to t=
he=20
reciprocal compensation issue can be reached in the marketplace,=0F" Ms.=20
Paoletta said.

The agreement comes as the FCC continues trying to craft an order addressin=
g=20
reciprocal compensation.  FCC Chairman William E. Kennard recently said he=
=20
wanted to complete work on the matter before his Jan. 19 departure from the=
=20
Commission (TR, Jan. 15).

Sources say that the Commissioners haven=0F't been able to agree on some as=
pects=20
of the proposed order and that the issue is likely to remain a priority eve=
n=20
after Mr. Kennard=0F's departure.

Financial analysts at Merrill Lynch & Co. saw the Level 3-SBC agreement as =
=0F"
modestly positive=0F" for both companies.  =0F"The agreement removes an ong=
oing=20
uncertainty relating to fluctuations in both costs for SBC and revenues for=
=20
Level 3,=0F" Merrill Lynch said.  =20

=0F"But in neither case is the impact sufficiently material for us to alter=
 our=20
revenue/expense projections, since the amounts fall within any normal range=
=20
of forecasting error,=0F" it said.

