is misguided; the regulatory hurdles are simply too high.

But Mr. Reingold said he thought a merger of SBC Communications, Inc., and=
=20
BellSouth Corp. might be possible in a few years=0F' time.  Those companies=
=20
already have merged their wireless units to form Cingular Wireless.  Bell=
=20
companies are well positioned for the current economic climate because they=
=20
typically outperform the stock market during recessions, he said.

Bell companies also will benefit from the turmoil in the competitive local=
=20
exchange carrier (CLEC) industry, whose inroads into local markets have=20
slowed as a shortage of funds has forced CLECs to cut back, Mr. Reingold=20
said.  =0F"I don=0F't believe the CLECs are going away,=0F" he said.  =0F"H=
owever, there=0F'
s a reality here . . .There are going to be fewer of them coming out of thi=
s=0F"=20
financial strife.

But the CLEC industry already is beginning to show signs of recovery, Credi=
t=20
Suisse First Boston analyst Mark Kastan said.  =0F"Sentiment has bottomed a=
nd=20
now is improving for the first time since spring of last year,=0F" he said.

After a long drought, financing now appears to be available for a select=20
group of CLECs, Mr. Kastan said.  McLeodUSA, Inc., and XO Communications,=
=20
Inc., are engaged in successful fund-raising efforts, he noted, and Time=20
Warner Telecom, Inc., is poised to attempt to raise $300 million through th=
e=20
sale of stock.

Report Offers Road Map To E-government Security

U.S. government agency officials now have guidance on how to address key=20
security concerns when offering Internet and other electronic services.  A=
=20
new publication, Securing Electronic Government, is the product of an=20
eight-month partnership of the Information Technology Association of Americ=
a=20
and two councils for the chief information officers (CIOs) and chief=20
financial officers (CFOs) in various governmental units.

The report covers electronic security concerns in three principal areas: =
=20
government electronic procurement, Web-based information services, and=20
governmental financial transactions.

=0F"We will. . .provide this to the federal community and, based on [the]=
=20
feedback, we will expand to other areas or refine these three areas,=0F" sa=
id=20
John Gilligan, deputy chief information officer and principal deputy=20
assistant secretary for business and information management for the U.S. Ai=
r=20
Force.

Mr. Gilligan stressed that the government needs to ensure the security of=
=20
electronic documents to avoid a loss of public confidence.  ITAA, the CIO=
=20
Council, and CFO Council initially met in May 2000 to develop guidelines fo=
r=20
adequate security.

The report states that information availability and integrity are the most=
=20
important priorities in providing Web-based information services, such as=
=20
data on taxes and unemployment rates.  Denial-of-service =0F"attacks=0F"=0F=
-attempts=20
to overload a Web site or server with information requests or e-mail messag=
es=0F-
and malicious data change were identified as the biggest threats to these=
=20
priorities.  =0F"Techniques do exist to safeguard these priorities,=0F" sai=
d David=20
Nelson, deputy chief information officer for the National Aeronautics and=
=20
Space Administration.

Regarding Internet-based government procurement, the report says that curre=
nt=20
industry security solutions for credit card purchases are adequate for=20
transactions of $100,000 or less, which make up the bulk of government onli=
ne=20
procurement deals.  Midsize procurements between $100,000 and $10 million=
=20
require heightened time sensitivity and confidence, necessitating more=20
extensive security precautions.  Purchases of more than $10 million require=
=20
customized solutions to ensure the integrity of data.

=0F"The public holds government to high standards. . .and [the government n=
eeds]=20
to ensure high public confidence,=0F" said Sky Lesher, deputy chief financi=
al=20
officer at the Department of the Interior.  =0F"They need to feel like they=
 are=20
in a secure environment.=0F"

Mr. Lesher said the report advocates a proactive approach to government=20
electronic security.  =0F"We prefer to be in a prevention mode rather than =
a=20
recovery mode,=0F" reacting to security breaches, he said.  Mr. Nelson adde=
d=20
that the report provides government managers with security =0F"know-how=0F"=
 from=20
industry representatives.

