FCC Suggests Streamlining Carrier-Change Process

The FCC has proposed rule changes that would make it easier for carriers to=
=20
sell or transfer exchanges.  The existing rules require carriers to get an=
=20
FCC rule waiver or obtain permission from all their customers before=20
switching them to a new service provider.=20

The Commission is considering an alternative scheme to its current =0F"
subscriber selection change=0F" rules as part of its =0F"biennial review=0F=
"=20
proceeding.  The Telecommunications Act of 1996 directs the FCC to conduct=
=20
reviews of its regulations every two years and to eliminate or revise those=
=20
rules that it finds are no longer necessary (see separate story).

Under section 64.1120 of the FCC=0F's current rules and section 258 of the=
=20
Communications Act of 1934, as amended, a carrier must obtain and verify a=
=20
customer=0F's permission to change his or her service provider.  Those rule=
s are=20
designed to deter =0F"slamming,=0F" or the authorized switching of a custom=
er=0F's=20
preferred carrier.=20

In a third further notice of proposed rulemaking released last week in Comm=
on=20
Carrier dockets 00-257 and 94-129, the FCC said it receives numerous reques=
ts=20
a month from carriers seeking waivers of those rules in order to complete=
=20
transactions involving transferring customer accounts to another carrier.

The Commission suggested an =0F"expedited process=0F" for such carriers whe=
reby the=20
carrier would be required only to notify its customers of the upcoming chan=
ge=20
and to provide them with an opportunity to switch carriers.  Comments are d=
ue=20
on the rulemaking notice 21 days after it is published in the Federal=20
Register.  Replies are due 10 days later.

Under the FCC=0F's proposal, the acquiring carrier would be required to not=
ify=20
the affected customers 30 days before the close of the transaction.  The=20
Commission is seeking input on the 30-day interval as well as the kind of=
=20
information that should be included in the notification.  It also proposed=
=20
that carriers notify the Commission of any such transactions.

In its rulemaking notice, the Commission asked if the advance-notice=20
requirements should differ based on the type of service that the carrier=20
provides.  It also asked if any additional obligations should be placed on=
=20
the carriers, such as establishing a toll-free number to answer customers=
=0F'=20
questions. =20

The Commission also asked how it could tailor the rules to prevent =0F"
unscrupulous=0F" carriers from selling customer accounts to evade enforceme=
nt=20
actions.

Verizon Wireless Asks FCC To Delay 700 MHz Band Auction

Citing a host of concerns, Verizon Wireless has asked the FCC for another=
=20
six-month delay of the auction of spectrum in the 700 megahertz band, which=
=20
is scheduled to begin March 6.  The auction has been delayed three times=20
already.

In a Jan. 18 letter to Wireless Telecommunications Bureau Chief Thomas J.=
=20
Sugrue, Verizon asked that the sale be postponed until September.  The lett=
er=20
was signed by John T. Scott, Verizon Wireless=0F' vice president and deputy=
=20
general counsel-regulatory law.

Mr. Scott said that if the auction was held as scheduled, potential bidders=
=20
wouldn=0F't have enough time to assess their spectrum needs because a reauc=
tion=20
of =0F"C=0F" and =0F"F=0F" block PCS (personal communications service) lice=
nses is still=20
ongoing (see separate story).  =0F"Short form=0F" applications for the 700 =
MHz band=20
auction are due Feb. 2, under the current schedule.

=0F"If the 700 MHz [band] auction begins on the current schedule, there wou=
ld be=20
no time for companies that are bidding in the PCS reauction to reassess the=
ir=20
business plans and develop bidding strategies for [the] 700 MHz [band=20
auction],=0F" Mr. Scott said.

The FCC immediately sought comments on Verizon=0F's request.  Comments are =
due=20
Jan. 24 and should reference DA 01-143.

Package Bidding Rules Cited

Mr. Scott also said carriers need more time to prepare because of new packa=
ge=20
bidding rules that will be used in the auction (TR, July 10, 2000).  He als=
o=20
cited continued concerns over when winning bidders would be able to build o=
ut=20
systems to use their newly licensed frequencies.  Similar concerns were cit=
ed=20
by the wireless industry when they successfully petitioned the FCC to move=
=20
the 700 MHz band auction from September 2000 to March 2001(TR, Aug. 7 and 2=
1,=20
2000).

Carriers had complained about the uncertainty of when the spectrum would be=
=20
available.  TV broadcasters with licenses for channels 60=0F-69 now occupy =
large=20
chunks of the spectrum and don=0F't have to leave until 2006 at the earlies=
t as=20
part of the transition to digital TV.

Mr. Scott said the uncertainty over when incumbent broadcasters would leave=
=20
the spectrum was still an issue.  He also noted that the FCC hadn=0F't yet=
=20
adopted proposed band-clearing mechanisms for those frequencies.  Even if=
=20
such mechanisms were adopted immediately, 700 MHz band auction bidders woul=
dn=0F'
t have time to use them, he said.

Mr. Scott also mentioned the high-level government-industry effort to=20
identify and allocate spectrum for third-generation (3G) services (see=20
separate story).  He noted that the 700 MHz band could be used for such=20
offerings and said the FCC should not auction that spectrum until it issued=
=20
an order allocating 3G bands.  That order is expected this summer.

=0F"There remains considerable uncertainty about the process for the auctio=
n,=20
the availability of the 700 MHz band itself, and the availability of=20
alternate spectrum,=0F" Mr. Scott said in the letter.  =0F"As a matter of s=
ound=20
spectrum-management policy, this spectrum should not be auctioned until the=
se=20
issues are resolved.=0F"

=0F"Conducting the auction before prospective bidders are able to make the=
=20
necessary assessments about spectrum use will jeopardize the efficient=20
assignment of this spectrum and ultimately disserve the public interest,=0F=
" he=20
added.  =0F"Greater certainty will enable the 700 MHz band to realize its f=
ull=20
economic and public benefit.=0F"

A spokesman for the Cellular Telecommunications & Internet Association told=
=20
TR that Verizon Wireless=0F' request to delay the auction =0F"is legitimate=
=0F" and=20
said the trade group planned to file comments in support of a postponement.

During a briefing with reporters last week before Verizon Wireless=0F' lett=
er=20
was submitted (see separate story), Commissioner Harold W. Furchtgott-Roth=
=20
said he had opposed the previous delays of the auction and would oppose any=
=20
effort to put it off further.  =0F"I would be very disappointed if there we=
re=20
any more delays,=0F" he said.

Ex-RSA Cellular Licensee Meets Judicial Skepticism

A three-judge panel of the U.S. Appeals Court in Washington expressed=20
skepticism at a former cellular licensee=0F's argument that the FCC wrongly=
=20
revoked its license for =0F"lack of candor.=0F"  Alee Cellular Com-municati=
ons had=20
falsely maintained that all of its partners were U.S. citizens.

The judges appeared to agree with the FCC=0F's contention that substantial=
=20
evidence showed the licensee=0F's partners knowingly deceived the agency to=
=20
retain a rural service area (RSA) license for Catron, N.M.  The license was=
=20
awarded by lottery in 1988, when noncitizens were barred from holding an=20
ownership stake in FCC licensees.

Hearing oral arguments in Alee Cellular Commun-ications v. FCC (case no.=20
99-1460) Jan. 16 were Chief Judge Harry T. Edwards and Judges Douglas H.=20
Ginsburg and A. Raymond Randolph.

In 1992, FCC Administrative Law Judge Walter C. Miller ruled that Alee had=
=20
told the Commission falsely that all of its 14 partners were U.S. citizens=
=20
when it knew one wasn=0F't (TR, Jan. 11, 1993).  The finding was part of a=
=20
broader proceeding in which Mr. Miller found that nearly two dozen cellular=
=20
license applicants, including Alee, had agreed to share with each other the=
=20
revenue earned using RSA licenses.  Those =0F"risk-sharing agreements=0F" w=
ere a=20
violation of FCC rules, the ALJ found..

The FCC=0F's review board upheld Alee=0F's license revocation in 1994.  In =
1997,=20
the full Commission upheld the decision, saying Alee=0F's =0F"lack of cando=
r=0F"=20
required the revocation (TR, June 9, 1997).

Alee:  License Revocation Unfair

Alee attorney Philip J. Mause told the court that the FCC arbitrarily and=
=20
capriciously relied on Mr. Miller=0F's findings about the credibility of=20
witnesses that had testified in a hearing on the risk-sharing agreements. =
=20
Mr. Mause said Mr. Miller compiled no written record of his judgments about=
=20
the witnesses to indicate why he found them credible or incredible.

Mr. Mause also contended that the FCC rejected substantial, credible eviden=
ce=20
that showed that Alee=0F's partners hadn=0F't intended to deceive the Commi=
ssion=20
regarding the noncitizen partner.  He also said the agency=0F's decision wa=
s not=20
supported by substantial evidence.

Even if there was such evidence to indicate a lack of candor, Mr. Mause sai=
d,=20
the punishment of license revocation was too harsh considering that (1) Ale=
e=20
reported the infraction to the agency and (2) other licensees in similar=20
situations had received more mild sanctions.

But FCC attorney Joel Marcus told the court that before upholding the licen=
se=20
revocation, the Commission conducted an independent review of the case, in=
=20
which it arrived at the same conclusion Mr. Miller had.

Mr. Marcus said the agency=0F's decision was supported by substantial evide=
nce. =20
=0F"That standard is easily met here,=0F" he said, citing the testimony of=
=20
witnesses and documentary evidence.

Mr. Marcus also said the rule violations by other licensees were not as=20
severe as Alee=0F's.  He added that agencies are given broad deference in=
=20
developing sanctions for rule violations.

The judges seemed to agree with the Commission=0F's argument.  =0F"It looke=
d to me=20
like it was doing its own independent evaluation,=0F" Judge Randolph said o=
f the=20
FCC.

=0F"They rely on documentary evidence, which they cite,=0F" Judge Edwards a=
dded. =20
Judge Ginsburg noted that the FCC cited both documentary evidence as well a=
s=20
evidence of the witnesses=0F' demeanor in reaching its decision to uphold t=
he=20
license revocation.

