CLECs Seek Cautious Approach to Regulating Their Access Fees; AT&T, WorldCo=
m=20
Want Caps

Many competitive local exchange carriers (CLECs) seem resigned to the FCC=
=0F's=20
adoption of a =0F"benchmark=0F" rate essentially capping the access charges=
 they=20
can levy on interexchange carriers (IXCs). =20

But they urged the FCC to take a cautious approach, recognizing that they=
=20
often have higher costs than incumbent local exchange carriers (ILECs),=20
particularly if they serve rural areas.

IXCs oppose any effort to exempt CLECs operating in rural areas from=20
complying with future benchmark rates.  Some CLECs and IXCs agreed that a=
=20
recent proposal from the Association for Local Telecommunications Services=
=20
(ALTS) offered at least a step toward resolving the simmering disputes=20
between CLECs and IXCs over access charges.

Seeking additional comments in its long-running proceeding in Common Carrie=
r=20
dockets 96-262 and 97-146, the FCC late last year asked parties to address=
=20
(1) the need for a =0F"rural exemption=0F" to any benchmark established for=
 CLECs=0F'=20
interstate access charges, and (2) the extent of abuses by CLECs in setting=
=20
terminating and originating access rates.

The Association for Communications Enterprises (ASCENT) reiterated its call=
=20
for the FCC to adopt =0F"safe harbor=0F" ranges for CLEC access charges; ch=
arges=20
within those ranges would be deemed reasonable and lawful.

ASCENT said there was =0F"significant merit=0F" to the ALTS proposal (TR, J=
an. 15),=20
which would impose ceilings on CLECs=0F' access charges and bar IXCs=0F' =
=0F"
self-help=0F" actions=0F-meaning their refusal to pay CLEC access charges t=
hat they=20
deem excessive.

In joint comments, e.spire Communications, Inc., KMC Telecom, Inc., Talk.co=
m=20
Holding Corp., and XO Communications, Inc., supported ALTS=0F' Guaranteed=
=20
Reduced Exchange Access Tariffs (GREAT) proposal.

=0F"The GREAT proposal recognizes that the entire industry can benefit from=
 the=20
establishment of benchmark access rates that are deemed reasonable by the=
=20
Commission and that the access charge rates of ILECs and CLECs are not=20
readily comparable, primarily because ILECs and CLECs do not necessarily=20
employ the same rate structures or network architectures,=0F" they said.

Other CLEC comments didn=0F't address the GREAT proposal directly and urged=
 the=20
FCC to proceed with caution=0F-if at all=0F-in imposing a benchmark limit o=
n CLEC=20
access charge rates.

=0F"The vast majority of access charges assessed by CLECs are comparable to=
=20
those of ILECs, which is significant in and of itself given the higher cost=
s=20
CLECs face in providing such access,=0F" said Focal Communications Corp., R=
CN=20
Telecom Services, Inc., and Winstar Communications, Inc., in joint comments=
.

If the FCC sets a benchmark for CLEC access rates, it should be done =0F"on=
 the=20
basis of ensuring that CLECs are able to collect their rightful charges and=
=20
that their customers are able to make and receive long distance calls,=0F" =
they=20
said.  They supported an exception to the benchmark for CLECs serving rural=
=20
and other high-cost areas.

Z-Tel Communications, Inc., also supported the use of a benchmark but oppos=
ed=20
mandatory detariffing for CLEC access rates, regardless of their level.  (T=
he=20
GREAT proposal envisions mandatory detariffing for charges above the=20
specified ceilings).=20

Requiring CLECs to detariff would allow ILECs to continue to =0F"bind IXCs =
with=20
tariffs,=0F" while Z-Tel and other CLECs would have to negotiate access=20
arrangements with hundreds of IXCs, it said.  =0F"By forcing CLECs to incur=
=20
negotiation costs not incurred by incumbents, mandatory detariffing raises =
a=20
barrier to entry in local exchange markets,=0F" Z-Tel said.

McLeodUSA Telecommunications Services, Inc., said the record =0F"does not=
=20
clearly establish=0F" the need for regulation of CLEC access charges.  Any=
=20
FCC-established benchmark rate for CLEC access charges thus should =0F"refl=
ect=20
the higher costs that CLECs incur in providing access service and provide a=
n=20
exemption for CLECs providing service to customers outside of defined=20
metropolitan statistical areas,=0F" he said.

CTSI, Inc., and Madison River Communications said the FCC should ensure tha=
t=20
any benchmark system =0F"does not legally, or [practically], prescribe a ra=
te=20
structure for CLECs.=0F"  The FCC would need to establish a methodology for=
 =0F"
converting rates of CLECs that choose=0F" a different rate structure from t=
hat=20
reflected in the benchmark rate, they said.  For instance, some CLECs choos=
e=20
not to charge a separate presubscribed interexchange carrier charge.

USTA:  No Rules Necessary

The U.S. Telecom Association said the FCC should not regulate CLEC access=
=20
rates.  =0F"A benchmark should not be adopted based on the arguments raised=
 in=20
this or any other proceeding by AT&T,=0F" it said.  =0F"Neither AT&T nor an=
y IXC=20
should be permitted to unilaterally determine which CLECs=0F' access rates =
are=20
too high and, therefore, which CLECs=0F' access services it will not purcha=
se.=0F"

USTA said the record didn=0F't justify imposing a benchmark rate for CLECs=
=0F'=20
access fees.  =0F"At a time when the Commission is seeking to encourage=20
competition and reduce regulation in competitive areas, new regulations=20
imposed on competitive entrants are not justified,=0F" it said.

The National Telephone Cooperative Association said a single nationwide=20
benchmark for CLEC access charges would lead to =0F"further disputes,=0F" =
=0F"possibly=20
result in confiscatory rates,=0F" and =0F"continue to hinder the developmen=
t of=20
facilities-based competition in poorly served rural areas.=0F"  The FCC sho=
uld=20
establish a separate benchmark for rural CLECs or create some other =0F"
regulatory alternative=0F" to allow them to recover their legitimate costs,=
 NTCA=20
said.

The FCC should not create a =0F"rural exemption=0F" to any prohibition on C=
LECs=0F'=20
tariffing rates above those charged by the ILEC in a given service area, sa=
id=20
AT&T Corp.  =0F"There is neither a legal nor an economic justification for=
=20
creating any exclusion for =0F`rural=0F' CLECs=0F" from a general rule link=
ing CLEC=20
and ILEC access rate levels in the same service area, it said.

A rural exemption would =0F"improperly support operations of a class of CLE=
Cs in=20
some as-yet-undefined =0F`rural=0F' areas through subsidies that are implic=
it in=20
tariffed access rates that are higher than those of the ILEC operating in t=
he=20
same geographic service territory,=0F" AT&T said.  Plus, the exemption woul=
d =0F"
inequitably place the burden of funding these CLECs=0F' subsidies in rural =
areas=20
solely upon those carriers=0F' access customers (including, in particular, =
IXCs=20
such as AT&T that serve large numbers of end users in nonurban regions),=0F=
" it=20
said.

WorldCom, Inc., joined AT&T in opposition to a rural exemption.  A single,=
=20
nationwide benchmark is the =0F"most effective, most easily administered wa=
y to=20
bring about CLEC access charge reductions,=0F" it said.

The =0F"general approach=0F" advocated in ALTS=0F' GREAT proposal is =0F"co=
nsistent with=20
sound public policy and merits serious consideration,=0F" WorldCom said.  I=
t=20
worked with ALTS in developing the proposal but said it didn=0F't support a=
ll of=20
its provisions.  Specifically, it opposed ALTS=0F' recommendation for a=20
six-month transition period before implementing a tariff ceiling.  WorldCom=
=20
said such a lengthy transition period was unnecessary.

WorldCom also submitted data on access charges that it said showed that man=
y=20
CLECs charge substantially more than ILECs.  Nearly one third of the CLECs=
=20
from which WorldCom purchases switched access services charge rates that ar=
e =0F"
more than five times higher=0F" than the average rates of ILECs.

=0F"IXCs will not be able to continue to absorb these costs for much longer=
,=0F"=20
WorldCom said.  =0F"Unless the Commission takes action, it is inevitable th=
at=20
IXCs will begin blocking switched access traffic from all CLECs with the=20
highest charges.=0F"

