Proposal To Streamline Service-Quality Reporting Gets Booed from All Sides;=
=20
Some Question Timing

The FCC=0F's proposal to reduce service-quality reporting requirements for=
=20
incumbent local exchange carriers (ILECs) got a big thumbs-down last week a=
s=20
state regulators, end-user interests, and competitive carriers argued the=
=20
need for the ILEC data.  And even the ILECs themselves=0F-which ostensibly =
would=20
benefit from the reduced obligations=0F-objected to portions of the plan.

Competitive carriers and small to midsize ILECs took issue with the FCC=0F'=
s=20
proposal to subject them to the same service-quality reporting requirements=
=20
that large ILECs must follow.  And state regulators in particular worried=
=20
that reducing the amount of available service-quality data could hamper sta=
te=20
proceedings.

Overall, most parties commenting last week on the proposal criticized it fo=
r=20
adding=0F-rather than eliminating=0F-regulations.  The rulemaking proposal =
in=20
Common Carrier docket 00-229 was undertaken as part of the Commission=0F's=
=20
biennial regulatory review, which is required by the Telecommunications Act=
=20
of 1996.

The biennial reviews are aimed at reducing regulations that are no longer=
=20
necessary as a result of increased competition (TR, Nov. 13, 2000, and=20
separate story in this issue).  Many industry members and state regulators=
=20
commenting last week questioned whether competition in local markets had=20
developed sufficiently to warrant streamlining the reporting requirements.

ILECs are required to submit to the FCC data about their performance in=20
providing retail service to end-user customers.  The data is submitted in t=
he=20
carriers=0F' Automated Reporting Management Information System (ARMIS) repo=
rts. =20
Citing increases in competition in local markets, the FCC had proposed, amo=
ng=20
other measures, slashing the number of reporting categories from 30 to six=
=20
and making the data more consumer-oriented.

States:   We Need ILEC Data

The National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners said that=20
monitoring ILECs=0F' service quality is particularly important =0F"in situa=
tions=20
where no competitive alternatives exist.=0F"  It noted that =0F"large incum=
bents=20
still hold in excess of 98% of at least the residential market across the=
=20
country,=0F" and several large ILECs have reported =0F"long-term negative t=
rend[s]=20
in service quality.=0F"  It pointed to instances in which state regulators=
=20
relied on the data reported to the FCC to make decisions about an ILEC=0F's=
=20
service quality. =20

The Florida Public Service Commission not only objected to any reductions i=
n=20
reporting requirements but also pressed the FCC to require ILECs to submit=
=20
even more specific data.  It said ILECs=0F' service-quality data should be =
=0F"
disaggregated=0F" to a state or smaller geographic level to give customers =
more=20
useful information.  =0F"It is easy to demonstrate high-quality service=20
performance overall while performing poorly in small geographic areas,=0F" =
it=20
said.

The Wyoming Public Service Commission questioned the timing of the=20
deregulatory proceeding.  Under the Act=0F's biennial review provisions, th=
e FCC=20
is required to examine its regulations to determine whether they are=20
necessary =0F"as a result of economic competition between providers.=0F" =
=20
Competition has had very little influence on the residential local exchange=
=20
market nationally, the Wyoming PCS said, adding that competition in Wyoming=
=20
is nascent.=20

=0F"Why would customers living in rural America, much of which is served by=
=20
price cap companies without competitive options, want to limit the=20
service-quality data that could be used by state and federal regulators?=0F=
" the=20
PSC asked.  =0F"It is too soon to narrow the focus of the quality-of-servic=
e=20
reporting to only that desired or needed by customers in a competitive=20
market.=0F"

The service-quality data reported to the FCC is important because it =0F"ca=
n be=20
compared across state lines,=0F" the Indiana Utility Regulatory Commission =
said.=20
 And the reporting requirements are useful even in a competitive service=20
market, the IURC added.  =0F"The FCC and the states must be vigilant, ensur=
ing=20
that unwarranted deregulation does not cause service quality to deteriorate=
,=0F"=20
it said.

The Illinois Commerce Commission asked the FCC to ensure that states be abl=
e=20
to impose additional service-quality reporting requirements in the absence =
of=20
federal requirements.  In its rulemaking notice, the FCC sought comments on=
 =0F"
alternative ways the FCC can continue to work with states=0F" on service-qu=
ality=20
issues.

The Wisconsin Public Service Commission acknowledged that streamlining=20
service-quality reporting requirements might be justified.  But some of the=
=20
FCC=0F's proposals go =0F"too far,=0F" it said, and prevent states from acc=
essing=20
meaningful data.  Monitoring service quality still =0F"is one of the most=
=20
important regulatory roles,=0F" the Wisconsin PSC said.

The FCC=0F's reference in its rulemaking notice to deregulation in the airl=
ine=20
industry is =0F"interesting,=0F" the Texas Public Utility Commission said. =
 =0F"
Competition in that industry has driven the need to create the reporting of=
=20
basic comparative retail performance data.=0F"  It said that during times o=
f=20
industry =0F"transition,=0F" regulators must have access to service data to=
 prevent=20
=0F"backsliding.=0F"

The federal service-quality reports are often used in state proceedings=20
evaluating the Ameritech Corp. telcos=0F' service, the Michigan Public Serv=
ice=20
Commission said.  =0F"These reports have allowed us to monitor [Ameritech=
=0F's=20
performance in] our state [and] compare . . .it to that of other states in =
a=20
meaningful way.=0F"

The Ohio Public Utilities Commission supported the FCC=0F's proposal to req=
uire=20
ILECs to submit data that is more useful to consumers. The FCC had suggeste=
d=20
that carriers report consumer-oriented data including time required for=20
installation, maintenance, and repair of equipment.  The Ohio commission sa=
id=20
ILECs wouldn=0F't need to =0F"develop or retain any data that they do not c=
urrently=20
keep for their own business practices.=0F"=20

End Users Say Data Is =0F`Crucial=0F'

End-user groups mostly opposed reductions in service-quality reporting, whi=
ch=20
they said gives customers a means of making informed decisions about=20
telecommunications service providers.  Most supported various extensions of=
=20
the FCC=0F's data reporting rules.

The FCC should continue to require carriers to submit service-quality data=
