SBC Communications, Inc., was skeptical of the FCC=0F's proposal to use ARM=
IS=20
data to inform consumers.  The information in ARMIS reports isn=0F't availa=
ble=20
to the public in an accessible format and doesn=0F't allow customers to com=
pare=20
a wide range of carriers, SBC said.=20

The Independent Telephone & Telecommunications Alliance, which comprises=20
midsize ILECs, strongly objected to the FCC=0F's proposal to extend=20
service-reporting requirements to all its members.  The FCC currently=20
requires only ILECs that are regulated by a price cap mechanism to file=20
service-quality reports.

ITTA objected to the FCC=0F's introducing the proposal during a biennial re=
view=20
proceeding.  =0F"It is unclear under what authority the Commission seeks to=
=20
extend service-quality reporting burdens to new classes of carriers and=20
service providers=0F" in such a proceeding, it said.

Imposing such conditions on carriers that serve less than 2% of the nation=
=0F's=20
access lines would place an unfair burden on small and rural carriers, ITTA=
=20
said.  =0F"Congress has long endorsed differentiating between LECs [local=
=20
exchange carriers] on the basis of size,=0F" it added.

Requiring rural LECs to provide service-quality data isn=0F't necessary, th=
e=20
National Telephone Cooperative Association said.  =0F"Rural LEC customers l=
iving=20
in small, closely-knit communities are intimately familiar with the quality=
=20
of service provided by rural LECs.  It is hard to see how such data would b=
e=20
more valuable to consumers than the reputation a company has in its local=
=20
market.=0F"

Small and rural carriers are =0F"focused on their communities, and they res=
pond=20
quickly to problems because they are not insulated from the consumer by=20
distance or size,=0F" NTCA added.

A group of small ILECs from Vermont said in a joint filing that they alread=
y=20
submit service-quality reports to the state commission, and additional=20
reporting requirements for smaller ILECs would be =0F"an unnecessary and=20
inefficient use of resources.=0F"  The carriers were Franklin Telephone Co.=
,=20
Ludlow Telephone Co., Northfield Telephone Co., Perkinsville Telephone Co.,=
=20
Shoreham Telephone Co., Topsham Telephone Co., Vermont Telephone Co., Inc.,=
=20
and Waitsfield-Fayston Telephone Co., Inc.

CLECs, IXCs Want More Data

Most CLECs had harsh words for the FCC=0F's proposal to extend service-qual=
ity=20
reporting requirements to other classes of carriers, including CLECs.  Most=
=20
blasted the plan as favoring ILECs and pushed for additional reporting=20
requirements.

=0F"Streamlining regulations does not lead to a more competitive market but=
=20
rather should be a response to a market that has already moved toward=20
competition,=0F" the Association for Local Telecommunications Services said=
. =20
Regulations should be reduced only to the extent that there is a =0F"proven=
=20
level of competition,=0F" ALTS said.

Some of the reporting requirements that the FCC is considering eliminating=
=20
provide =0F"vital=0F" data to CLECs, ALTS said.  =0F"The Commission=0F's ac=
tions in this=20
proceeding could also be setting a dangerous precedent=0F" for other=20
proceedings, it added.  It cited proceedings related to section 271 of the=
=20
Act, under which Bell companies can apply for authority to provide in-regio=
n=20
interLATA (local access and transport area) services once they open their=
=20
local exchange markets to competition.

In future section 271 applications, the Bells =0F"may argue that they are n=
o=20
longer required to report submetrics vital to OSS (operation support system=
)=20
performance and [preventing] backsliding,=0F" ALTS said.

In joint comments, the Competitive Telecommunications Association, e.spire=
=20
Communications, Inc., KMC Telecom, Inc., Net2000 Communications, Inc., XO=
=20
Communications, Inc., and Z-Tel Communications, Inc., said the FCC=0F's=20
proposals would reduce regulation of ILECs while increasing regulation of=
=20
CLECs.

=0F"If anything, a review of the state of competition in the local exchange=
=20
market reveals that the Commission should institute additional reporting=20
requirements for ILEC provisions of [unbundled network elements] and=20
wholesale services the CLECs,=0F" the CLECs said.

Measuring CLEC service quality is unnecessary, since CLECs are =0F"beholden=
 to=20
the ILECs in their provisioning of services,=0F" Focal Communications Corp.=
=20
said.  Requiring CLECs to report such data would =0F"further hinder competi=
tion=20
by placing an additional burden on carriers already experiencing difficulti=
es=20
competing with ILECs.=0F"

The FCC should use this proceeding as =0F"an ideal opportunity to police th=
e=20
incumbents=0F' market-opening behaviors,=0F" Covad Communications Co. said.=
  It=20
suggested that the FCC collect data on ILECs=0F' wholesale service quality =
and=20
then use that data to =0F"streamline the section 271 and enforcement=20
processes.=0F"  This could =0F"end the =0F`he said, she said=0F' battle of =
data=20
reconciliation,=0F" it added.

Advanced TelCom Group, Inc., opined that the reasons the FCC mandated the=
=20
reporting requirements =0F"remain valid today.=0F"  It pointed out that inc=
reases=20
in the reporting requirements had been included as conditions of the FCC=0F=
's=20
approval of several mergers involving large ILECs.  =0F"It seems wholly=20
inconsistent to increase the reporting requirements for SBC and Bell Atlant=
ic=20
[now Verizon] and, at the same time, propose reducing the reporting=20
requirements for price cap LECs generally,=0F" Advanced TelCom said.

Making the reporting requirements voluntary, rather than mandatory, as the=
=20
FCC suggested, =0F"would defeat the purpose=0F" of the requirements, Dynerg=
y CLEC=20
Communications, Inc., said.  The FCC=0F's proposed changes of the reporting=
=20
system =0F"are unnecessary and will yield an inaccurate service picture of=
=20
carrier performance.=0F"

CLEC reporting requirements aren=0F't necessary, since CLEC customers are=
=20
service-quality=0F-sensitive, Teligent Inc., said.  =0F"To the extent that =
a CLEC=0F's=20
service quality is not comparable to an ILEC=0F's, its customers will migra=
te=20
back to the ILEC and the CLEC will find itself without customers.=0F"

EarthLink, Inc., applauded the FCC=0F's proposal to require ILECs to report=
