Rohde:  Spectrum Management Holds Key Challenge for Future

Spectrum management, including identifying and allocating spectrum for=20
third-generation (3G) services, is one of the key issues facing federal=20
regulators in the coming year, says Gregory L. Rohde, who last week finishe=
d=20
his service as head of the National Telecom-munications and Information=20
Administration.

At a news conference last week, Mr. Rohde discussed NTIA=0F's achievements =
over=20
the past year and its future challenges.  The Commerce Department agency=20
outlined many of these points in the annual report it submitted to Congress=
=20
last week.

Citing highlights from the past year, Mr. Rohde noted numerous=20
spectrum-management issues, including ultrawideband (UWB) technology testin=
g,=20
the Clinton administration=0F's effort to identify and allocate bands for 3=
G=20
services (see separate story), and U.S. success at last year=0F's World=20
Radiocommunication Conference (WRC-2000).

Mr. Rohde also cited NTIA=0F's efforts to bridge the =0F"digital divide,=0F=
" its=20
Technology Opportunities Program, and its work with the FCC to improve=20
telecom access on tribal lands.   NTIA has revitalized its Minority=20
Telecommunications Development Program, Mr. Rohde said, and it has worked t=
o=20
protect online privacy and raise awareness about online profiling.

Looking to the future, he stressed the importance of allocating 3G spectrum=
=20
and said regulators must realize the implications of the shift from=20
traditional telephony to data-transmission services.  He said the nation mu=
st=20
continue to close the digital divide for Americans who don=0F't have Intern=
et=20
access, and the universal service support system for =0F"high-cost=0F" area=
s must=20
be reformed.

Mr. Rohde said the U.S. should reach out to developing countries, or it cou=
ld=20
find itself isolated in international telecom policy-making.  =0F"I firmly=
=20
believe that it=0F's in our self-interest to work with the developing world=
 to=20
get more people online,=0F" Mr. Rohde said.

At the International Telecommunication Union=0F's World Telecommunication=
=20
Standardization Assembly last fall, the U.S. was the only ITU member countr=
y=20
that objected to cost-sharing for international Internet interconnection an=
d=20
targets for international settlement rates (TR, Oct. 9, 2000).

=0F`Datacasting=0F' License Caps To Be Imposed in Australia

The Australian Communications Authority intends to impose ownership limits =
on=20
=0F"datacasting=0F" transmitter licenses, which it expects to auction in th=
e first=20
half of the year. =20

Datacasting providers would be limited to holding one license in each of th=
e=20
nation=0F's eight datacasting service areas.  The regulatory body is puttin=
g its=20
spectrum-allocation plans in final form.

Richard Alston, Minister of Communications, Information Technology, and the=
=20
Arts, said Jan. 18 that ownership restrictions were necessary to ensure=20
competition.  =0F"At this early stage of a new industry, it is important to=
=20
encourage the maximum amount of competition in the market, and this is best=
=20
done by imposing a limit on the number of licenses that may be purchased by=
=20
one player [=0F`or its associates=0F'] in each market,=0F" he said.=20

Upon completing its spectrum engineering and allocation plans, the Australi=
an=20
Communications Authority probably will defer any further increases in=20
spectrum availability in the eight service areas =0F"until at least 2003,=
=0F" Mr.=20
Alston said. =20

Meanwhile, the government has lifted obligations under the Telecommunicatio=
ns=20
Act of 1992 that would have required datacasters also to obtain carrier=20
licenses.  These actions will =0F"increase certainty for potential datacast=
ers,=0F"=20
he added.

The government hasn=0F't ruled out allocating datacasting licenses in regio=
ns=20
other than the eight specified service areas, =0F"once the channel planning=
 in=20
regional areas has been completed,=0F" Mr. Alston said.

Nigerian Sale Yields $855M For Three Cellular Licenses

A Nigerian auction of three cellular licenses concluded Friday, Jan. 19,=20
garnering $285 million for each license.  Spectrum auctions in Canada, New=
=20
Zealand, and Venezuela are ongoing.

The winning bidders in the Nigerian auction were Communication Investments=
=20
Ltd., Econet Wireless Nigeria Ltd., and MTN Nigeria Communications Ltd.  A=
=20
fourth license was reserved for state-run Nitel and its Mtel mobile phone=
=20
unit; the payment for that license also will be $285 million.  Five groups=
=20
bid on the licenses, which were awarded after three days of bidding.

In other international spectrum developments, a Canadian auction of=20
third-generation (3G) PCS (personal communications service) licenses opened=
=20
last week and generated $262.9 million Canadian (US$173.8 million) in bids =
by=20
Friday.  Seven companies are bidding on 62 licenses covering 16 markets.

In New Zealand, the first part of an auction for licenses in the 2 gigahert=
z=20
band is over after no new bids for management rights were submitted (TR, De=
c.=20
25, 2000).  A second phase of the auction is upcoming.

And in Venezuela, an auction on a third group of five wireless local loop=
=20
licenses continued with Empresa Nacional de Telecomunicaciones SA (Entel=20
Chile) and Digicel CA winning licenses with bids of $1.5 million and=20
$300,000, respectively (TR, Jan. 15).

