Court Allows Mobile Phone Lawsuit To Continue

A U.S. District Court judge in Louisiana is allowing a plaintiff to go=20
forward with a lawsuit that says the wireless industry should be required t=
o=20
include headsets with mobile phones to protect against the risks of radio=
=20
frequency (RF) exposure.

The wireless industry had asked the court to dismiss the litigation on the=
=20
grounds that the Food and Drug Administration=0F's authority to oversee mob=
ile=20
phone safety preempts court involvement.  But Judge Ivan L.R. Lemelle of th=
e=20
U.S. District Court in New Orleans rejected that argument last week and=20
allowed the case (Garrett J. Naquin et al. v. Nokia Mobile Phones, Inc., et=
=20
al. case no. 00-2023) to proceed.  A separate lawsuit against the industry=
=20
has been in filed in Maryland (see separate story).

The lawsuit, which was filed last year, says the mobile phone industry has=
=20
known of the potential health risks of the devices and should be required t=
o=20
reimburse consumers who already have purchased mobile phones without headse=
ts=20
and to provide headsets to those who buy phones in the future.  It also see=
ks=20
unspecified monetary damages for anguish and medical monitoring.

The lawsuit originally was filed in state court in New Orleans but was move=
d=20
to federal court at the request of the wireless industry. =20

New Orleans attorney Michael Allweiss told TR he planned to amend the lawsu=
it=20
to add at least one more plaintiff.  He is asking the court to certify the=
=20
lawsuit as a class action.

