FCC Reauction

Net bids in the FCC=0F's ongoing reauction of 422 =0F"C=0F" and =0F"F=0F" b=
lock PCS=20
(personal communications service) licenses hit $16.8 billion at the end of=
=20
bidding Friday, Jan. 19 (TR, Jan. 15).  The action continued to slow down,=
=20
with only 27 new bids submitted in the 73rd round.

Verizon Wireless still led all bidders, offering $8.8 billion. It was=20
followed by Alaska Native Wireless LLC, which is partly owned by AT&T=20
Wireless Services, Inc., which bid $2.8 billion.  Salmon PCS LLC=0F-partly =
owned=20
by Cingular Wireless LLC=0F-bid $2.3 billion.

The highest bids continued to be for licenses in the largest market, New Yo=
rk=20
City, with Verizon Wireless the high bidder on two licenses there and Alask=
a=20
Native Wireless the top bidder on a third.

Thirty-seven bidders remained eligible after bidding was completed Jan. 19.=
 =20
The reauction has moved into a phase that requires bidders to be more activ=
e=20
in each round to retain their bidding eligibility.

In a related development, the FCC affirmed its decision last year to modify=
=20
its rules for C and F block auctions (TR, Aug. 28, 2000).

In an order on reconsideration released in Wireless Telecommunications dock=
et=20
97-82, the Commission denied five petitions for reconsideration of the rule=
s=20
changes, which allow large entities to bid on some licenses while reserving=
=20
others for small businesses known as =0F"designated entities=0F" (DEs).  Th=
e FCC=20
said the changes balanced the needs of both large and small carriers.

