NTCA Makes Push for MAG Plan, Lifting Caps on Universal Service

Policy-makers need to realize that even though rural telcos serve only a=20
small percentage of the telecom market, their operations cover nearly 40% o=
f=20
the nation=0F's land and, in many cases, they=0F're entering multiple lines=
 of=20
business.  That=0F's the message the National Telephone Cooperative Associa=
tion=20
is carrying to the FCC and Congress as it seeks to garner more federal=20
support for some of its pet projects.

On Capitol Hill, NTCA plans to revive its legislative push to eliminate cap=
s=20
on the amount that individual carriers are eligible to receive in universal=
=20
service support, says Chief Executive Officer Michael Brunner.  The=20
association is considering broadening that proposal to include a broadband=
=20
tax credit plan, he says.

At the FCC, the group=0F's most pressing concern is getting quick adoption =
of=20
the multiassociation group (MAG) plan for overhauling the interstate access=
=20
charge system for telcos operating under rate-of-return regulation, Mr.=20
Brunner tells TR.  An edited transcript of our conversation follows.

TR:  What are NTCA=0F's top priorities for the 107th Congress?  Should we e=
xpect=20
to see your proposal from the last Congress to lift the universal service c=
ap?

Brunner:  The answer is yes.  As you know, we were instrumental in working=
=20
with [Sen. Conrad] Burns [R., Mont.] in getting that bill introduced in the=
=20
last session.  Obviously that=0F's a priority again, as the Rural Task Forc=
e has=20
sort of come up with half a loaf in recommending an index cap.

We see the Rural Task Force plan as better obviously than the current=20
situation, but we see it causing a problem down the road.  For example, if =
a=20
lot of acquisitions occur=0F-and I think they will=0F-then there=0F's going=
 to be a=20
need to upgrade all those lines. =20

The current cap won=0F't be adequate to do that, and we hope the Commission=
,=20
under any circumstances, wouldn=0F't go below what the Rural Task Force is=
=20
recommending.

TR:  That effort garnered bipartisan backing from key U.S. senators last=20
session.  What=0F's your strategy for expanding congressional support for i=
t in=20
the 107th Congress?

Brunner:  One way to do that might be to go back to the drafting of the=20
Telecommunications Act of 1996, when Congress really understood that we hav=
e=20
to give equal weight to the twin goals of competition and universal service=
. =20
Our feeling is that this Commission and the past Commissions, perhaps, may=
=20
have given more weight to competition and less to universal service.

It=0F's real clear in the statute that Congress thinks those issues are equ=
ally=20
weighted, and whether or not people like it, things cost more in rural=20
America.  If we really want to bring broadband services to all Americans, w=
e=20
can=0F't do it without some kind of support. =20

And if Congress is saying on the one hand, =0F"Deploy advanced services,=0F=
" it=20
seems odd to say on the other hand, =0F"We=0F're going to limit this cap, l=
imit the=20
support.=0F"

Rep. Nathan Deal [R., Ga.] was our key guy in the House on this last year,=
=20
and Sen. Burns in the Senate.  We=0F're working with a lot of other people,=
 too,=20
to see if we can=0F't be more comprehensive this time around.

For example, another key component of our plan could be some kind of tax=20
credit or a low-interest [Rural Utilities Service] loan.  And rather than=
=20
have one bill address this part and one for that part, we may have all of=
=20
those wind up in one comprehensive package.

On the broadband tax credit plan, the idea is to develop. . .a bill that=20
would enable carriers to claim a fairly substantial credit for deploying=20
broadband services to rural areas.  We don=0F't want it to be technology-=
=20
specific, where you end up with something that seems to favor one technolog=
y=20
over the other.

I don=0F't want to be too specific because we=0F're still working with a nu=
mber of=20
our own members to work out the details.  We don=0F't have a perfect packag=
e=20
yet. . .and I don=0F't think it would be hugely expensive.  We realize no o=
ne=0F's=20
going to go for a big spending bill, especially with the economy sort of=20
turning right now, or potentially turning.

But we=0F're still moving forward on this.  Our annual meeting will be held=
 the=20
first week in February, and that=0F's when we=0F're really going to start h=
ashing=20
out some of these things and talking about some overall policy resolutions.

TR:  One thing you haven=0F't mentioned is a deregulatory approach to broad=
band=20
service deployment.  Why?

Brunner:  We really haven=0F't been drawn to that approach for a lot of rea=
sons,=20
one being that we think a broadband tax credit bill is a more targeted=20
approach that really gets at the issue.  If the policy-makers really want t=
o=20
deploy broadband services nationwide, and they say they do, this is the way=
