TR:  Let=0F's talk about your recent white paper recommending that universa=
l=20
service =0F"high-cost=0F" support be =0F"nonportable=0F" [TR, Jan. 15].  Ho=
w did you come=20
to this conclusion, and where do you go with it?

Brunner:  What we=0F've got there is a study with some actual data.  It sho=
ws=20
that introducing competition in rural areas is ultimately going to lead to=
=20
less broadband technology deployment. =20

Our next step is to try to convince regulators that artificial competition=
=20
doesn=0F't work.  If there=0F's an actual market for more than one carrier,=
 then=20
indeed consumers might benefit.  But there aren=0F't great public benefits,=
 as=20
we see it, to artificially creating competition where markets don=0F't=20
ordinarily permit competition as a matter of course.

Our point is that sometimes the regulators try to take an urban solution an=
d=20
inject it into rural America.  It makes sense to induce competition in=20
downtown areas like Los Angeles or Chicago, where the average Bell company=
=20
has anywhere from 130 to 150 customers per mile.  But we only have four or=
=20
five or six per mile=0F-very small numbers.

We would argue that it=0F's hard for one carrier to really make it in these=
=20
markets.  And if they force a second one or a third one in, it splits up th=
e=20
business even more, and no one=0F's going to have the wherewithal to delive=
r=20
broadband services.

One of our main themes on Capitol Hill and at the Commission is that=20
policy-makers need to appreciate the fact that rural areas are different. =
=20
Most policy-makers, as you might imagine, have an urban background. . .Our=
=20
job is to continue to try to educate people about the differences between=
=20
urban and rural areas.

We=0F've done that with some success.  For example, we=0F've had several of=
 the=20
Commissioners come out and speak at our meetings, spend time with our=20
members, talk with them one-on-one.  [Commissioner Harold W.]=20
Furchtgott-Roth, for example, came out and visited a small telco with us.  =
We=20
really look for opportunities to give them a greater appreciation of these=
=20
kinds of things.

Going back to Congress, we also want to really caution people not to reopen=
=20
up the Telecommunications Act or to pass a new Act until some of the key=20
rural issues are resolved.  We=0F're now going on five years since passage =
of=20
the Telecommunications Act, and some of our members still can=0F't plan bec=
ause=20
they don=0F't know about [the outcome of] access charge reform.  As you kno=
w,=20
our members get better than 50% of their revenues from access charges.

The biggest decisions for the new Commission will be on high-cost support a=
nd=20
access charge reform.  Both the MAG and the Rural Task Force plans have=20
touched on that.

TR:  Switching gears to the incoming Bush administration, how do you forese=
e=20
the Department of Agriculture=0F's Rural Utilities Service [RUS] developing=
 over=20
the next few years?  Will there be major changes?

Brunner:  Actually, to be honest, no one knows.  My sense is that the RUS n=
o=20
longer is the political issue it used to be because when people look at it,=
=20
they=0F're seeing that the cost of that program is so minute.  It=0F's some=
where=20
around $6 million or $7 million in interest subsidies for about $600 millio=
n=20
in loans.

And everyone thinks it does work well; there=0F's never been a default.  So=
 I=20
don=0F't sense we=0F're going to have an effort, as was made in the Reagan=
