administration, to really cut back on some of these things.  I could be=20
totally wrong, but my sense is it has enough respect and support on both=20
sides of the aisle.

Plus, the lending no longer is simply for the same =0F"plain old telephone=
=20
service=0F"; it=0F's now for some new things.

TR:  Let=0F's talk about NTCA=0F's membership.  What kind of efforts are un=
der way=20
to accommodate some of your members=0F' non-ILEC [incumbent local exchange=
=20
carrier] operations?

Brunner:  Many years ago there were questions about how our members would=
=20
adapt to change in competition.  My sense is that they=0F're adapting quite=
=20
well, as almost all of them are in multiple lines of business.  They=0F're=
=20
becoming Internet service providers, many of them are in the cable TV=20
business, most of them have wireless or broadcast satellite operations, som=
e=20
are resellers, and many are becoming CLECs [competitive local exchange=20
carriers].

They=0F've gotten into multiple lines of business, so they are becoming, in=
 a=20
lot of ways, more than ILECs.  We=0F've broadened our approach to assist th=
em in=20
some other areas.  So it=0F's a very active membership, some more than othe=
rs.

We have a new initiative called C3A.  It=0F's really an effort to get membe=
rs=20
who are thinking more competitively to get together and perhaps aggregate=
=20
their businesses with things like volume discounts. =20

I=0F've been very pleased with our membership=0F's willingness to grow and =
change. =20
For a while I thought they just might want to keep doing things the same ol=
d=20
way that has always worked for them.  But they really are changing.

We=0F're not the biggest player.  We=0F're only about 5% of the industry, b=
ut it=20
really is a critical 5%.  We represent roughly 40% of the land in this=20
country, but it=0F's a unique and critical part.

We would just really hope that the policy-makers would make it a priority t=
o=20
understand that the 5% we serve is as important as the whole.  That=0F's=20
something that some people miss.

